<TITLE> Michael Caine selects songs to chill by </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 NEW YORK, August 11 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Legendary British actor Michael Caine has played all manner of onscreen roles. Now, in his 70s, he's taking on a new role: DJ. Caine has put together a compilation CD, 'Cained,' that gathers such tasteful 'chill-out' classics as Chicane's 'No Ordinary Morning,' John Martyn's 'Sunshine's Better' and Roy Budd's 'Hurry to Me' along with St Germain's 'Rose Rouge,' Felix Da Housecat's rerub of Nina Simone's 'Sinnerman' and Bent's 'Swollen.' Universal Records will issue the set September 3 in Britain. "I've loved this type of music for years and have literally hundreds of CDs," Caine said of the mellow, generally slow-tempo genre. "I've been buying them for about 15 years and really know my way around." His sojourn into the music business came about through a fortuitous dinner at Elton John's mansion in Nice, France, during which the Academy Award winner impressed his host with his knowledge of music. Caine also admitted to a longtime passion for making compilations. By his reckoning, he has assembled 'literally thousands' of compilation tapes and CDs. "And with chill-out I suppose I finally found my fort
